JOHANNESBURG &#8211; South Africa&#8217;s rand retreated early on Tuesday in subdued overnight trade ahead of first quarter growth data set to show the economy bounced back from a previous contraction.At 0640 GMT, the rand traded at 12.7475 per dollar, 0.3% weaker than its close of 12.7100 overnight in New York.The rand has posted net gains of nearly 3% in June after S&amp;P Global Ratings and Fitch affirmed BB+ ratings following downgrades to subinvestment in April. Moody&#8217;s decision due on Friday.&#8220;The rand has continued to perform admirably, holding steady below the 13.0000 handle, some caution is advised as the move to the downside appears potentially stretched in the short term,&#8221; said analyst at Nedbank Capital Reezwana Sumad.Gross domestic product data for Q1 due at 0930 GMT. Reuters poll predicts 0.8% expansion following 0.3% contraction in previous quarter.Government bonds were weaker, with the yield on benchmark paper due in 2026 up 3 basis points to 8.465%.Stocks were set to open lower at 0700 GMT, with the JSE securities exchange&#8217;s Top-40 futures index down 0.4%.